  <datafield tag="545" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Fred E. Benz was an Ann Arbor, Michigan businessman. He joined his brothers in an Ann Arbor feed and implements business in 1911. The Benz Brothers business prospered as they expanded into the area of automobile accessories. In the twenties they opened a Chevrolet dealership. Benz relinquished control of Benz Brothers to his brother and became treasurer of the Ann Arbor Finance Company in 1928. In 1931 he left that position to become vice-president and secretary of the National Company in Ann</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="545" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Arbor. He retired in 1932. He and his wife Margaret began traveling in 1929 and continued to do so until his death in 1963. Benz was a skilled photographer and documented his travels on the reels of film which comprise this collection.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">The Fred Benz Collection consists of sixty-two reels of film shot by Benz on various trips. The series is divided by the name of the trip and includes footage of Africa (1939), color; Australia/New Zealand (1936), black and white; Guatemala (1950), color; Havana (1950), color; Mexico (undated), color; Russia (1937), black and white; South America (1948), color; and a World Cruise (1929), black and white. No one area is represented in depth and the value of the collection lies in being able to</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">experience a series of moments captured in time. The concentration is on filming people and locations. Most of the major cities of the world are represented as well as small towns and remote villages. It shows how people lived and often what they did. Benz captured life as it went on around him on these trips. The films depict peasant life in Russia and life-saving competitions in Australia. They convey a considerable amount of information about women and their lifestyles in the countries visited.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">One reel contains footage of construction on Mount Rushmore and another was used by the Department of the Navy during World War Two in order to study the footage of Kiskens, Norway. The collection also contains one 400 foot reel of commercially produced stock newsreel footage sold by Castle Films. It depicts the German invasion of Russia in 1941 and the counterattack in 1943 as seen from the Soviet point of view. The reel consists primarily of combat footage.</subfield>
  </datafield>
